<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How many floor joists do I need?", answer: "Divide the longer dimension (the wall the joists run parallel to) by your spacing and add one. A 16 ft × 12 ft room with joists at 16\" OC needs 16 × 12 / 16 = 12, plus one at the far end = 13 joists. The joists span the shorter 12 ft dimension." },
  { question: "What is the maximum span for a 2x10 floor joist?", answer: "Per IRC Table R502.3.1(1), a 2x10 SPF #2 joist at 16\" OC with 40 psf live load and 10 psf dead load can span about 15 ft 5 in. Southern Yellow Pine and Douglas Fir #2 reach about 16 ft 2 in. Tighter 12\" OC spacing extends spans; wider 24\" OC reduces them." },
  { question: "Should I use 2x8, 2x10, or 2x12 joists?", answer: "For spans up to about 12 ft use 2x8, 12 to 16 ft use 2x10, and 16 to 20 ft use 2x12. Always check the IRC table for your species, spacing, and load. For living areas use 40 psf live load; for attics with storage use 30 psf; for decks use 40 psf snow or live." },
  { question: "What does 'L/360 deflection' mean?", answer: "It means the joist is allowed to deflect no more than 1/360 of its span under live load. A 12 ft span can deflect up to 12 ft × 12 in ÷ 360 = 0.4 inches. This prevents bouncy floors and cracked finishes. Some designers prefer L/480 for tiled floors." },
  { question: "How far apart should joists be?", answer: "16 inches on center is the residential standard — it lets you use 3/4\" plywood or OSB subfloor and matches standard wall and truss spacing. 12\" OC is used for heavier loads or longer spans; 24\" OC is used with engineered I-joists or 7/8\"+ subfloor." }
]) %>

